<http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-9690722/R-HSA-9690722>
        a       <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0052553> , <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> ;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment>
                "This Reactome module describes modulation of IFIT proteins by diverse viral families that have evolved multiple strategies to evade IFIT-mediated restriction. Among RNA viruses, a common mechanism is acquisition of cap-1 structures, either by “cap-snatching” host mRNA fragments (e.g., in orthomyxoviruses) or through virally encoded or hijacked host 2′-O-methyltransferases, as in flaviviruses and coronaviruses (Daffis S et al., 2010; Zust R et al., 2011; reviewed by Hyde JL & Diamond MS 2015; Tsukamoto Y et al., 2024). Some viruses employ RNA secondary structures that shield the 5′ end from IFIT recognition, including the panhandle structures of bunyaviruses and arenaviruses (Hyde JL et al., 2014; Reynaud JM et al., 2015; Hankinson J et al., 2025). In addition, IFIT2 can bind adenylate–uridylate (AU)-rich elements in the 3′ UTRs of cellular and viral mRNAs, a mechanism that normally promotes translation of host interferon-stimulated genes but is co-opted by influenza virus to enhance viral protein synthesis (Yang Z et al., 2012; Tran V et al., 2020). Further, large DNA viruses such as vaccinia virus deploy proteins that directly antagonize IFIT activity (Liu R et al., 2019; Xie S et al., 2025), for example by targeting IFITs for proteasomal degradation, thereby counteracting their antiviral function (Liu R et al., 2019)." ;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label>
                "Viral strategies to evade IFIT action" ;
        <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/contributor>
                "Authored: Shamovsky, Veronica, 2020-05-22" , "GOC:reactome_curators" , "Reviewed: Hyde, Jennifer L, 2026-05-19" ;
        <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/date>
                "2026-07-02" ;
        <http://purl.org/pav/providedBy>
                "https://reactome.org" ;
        <http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboInOwl#hasDbXref>
                "R-HSA-9690722" ;
        <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower>
                <http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-9684482/R-HSA-9684482> ;
        <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note>
                "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

